{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Alex Piquero | honorific_suffix = | native_name = Alexis Russell Piquero | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|05|06}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = Cuban-American | fields = [[Criminology]] | workplaces = [[University of Texas at Dallas]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Maryland, College Park]] | thesis_title = An application of Stafford and Warr's reconceptualization of deterrence to drinking and driving | thesis_url = http://search.proquest.com/docview/304269392/B24022C3B1E747E5PQ/17?accountid=12948 | thesis_year = 1996 | doctoral_advisor = [[Raymond Paternoster]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = [[Wesley Jennings]] | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[American Society of Criminology]]'s Young Scholar and E-Mail Mentor of the Year Awards | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = [[Nicole Leeper Piquero]] | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Alexis Russell "Alex" Piquero''' (born May 6, 1970)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no98096873.html | title=Alexis Russell Piquero | work=Library of Congress | accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref> is a Cuban-American criminologist and the [[Ashbel Smith]] Professor of Criminology at the [[University of Texas at Dallas]] (UT-Dallas), where he is also the Associate Dean for Graduate Programs in the School of Economic, Political, and Policy Sciences. He has been ranked as the #1 criminologist in the world since 1996 by the number of peer-reviewed papers in criminology journals.<ref name=dallas>{{cite web | url=https://www.utdallas.edu/epps/faculty/alex-piquero/ | title=Alex R. Piquero | work=University of Texas at Dallas | accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref> In 2015, then-[[United States Attorney General]] [[Eric Holder]] appointed him to the [[Office of Justice Programs]] Science Advisory Board.<ref name=nbc/>
==Education and career== Piquero received his B.A. in 1992, his M.A. in 1994, and his Ph.D. in 1996. All three of his degrees were in criminology and criminal justice, and he received all of them from the [[University of Maryland, College Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.utdallas.edu/epps/faculty/cv/alex-piquero.pdf | title=Alex R. Piquero CV | accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref> After teaching at [[Florida State University]], the [[University of Maryland]], the [[John Jay College of Criminal Justice]], and other institutions, he joined the faculty of UT-Dallas in 2011.<ref name=dallas/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.utdallas.edu/chairs/profiles/piquero.html | title=Dr. Alex R. Piquero | work=University of Texas at Dallas | accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref>
==Research== The subjects Piquero has researched include the link between [[malnutrition]] and violence.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://mic.com/articles/155265/want-to-reduce-crime-in-america-try-giving-kids-better-food#.CtcovTWmy | title=Want to reduce crime in America? Try giving kids better food. | work=Mic | date=27 September 2016 | accessdate=29 September 2016 | author=Shah, Khushbu}}</ref> He has also co-authored a study showing that the arrest rate among [[National Football League]] players is lower than that for the American male population aged 20 to 39.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/aug/25/nfl-arrest-rate-study-us-population |title=Arrest rate in NFL lower than for general US population, 'surprising' study finds |website=The Guardian |publication-date=25 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/26/us/nfl-players-arrests-study/ |title=Study: NFL arrest rate lower than for all males ages 20-39 |last=Martin |first=Jill |website=CNN |publication-date=26 August 2015}}</ref> He has collaborated on several books, including the ''Handbook of Quantitative Criminology'' (edited by [[David Weisburd]]).<ref name=nbc>{{cite web | url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/what-i-ve-learned-our-talk-top-ranked-criminologist-alex-n522046 | title=What I've Learned: Our Talk with Top-Ranked Criminologist Alex Piquero | work=NBC News | date=24 February 2016 | accessdate=29 September 2016 | author=Cepeda, Esther}}</ref>
==Honors and awards== Piquero has received the [[American Society of Criminology]]'s Young Scholar and E-Mail Mentor of the Year Awards. He has also been a fellow of the American Society of Criminology and the [[Academy of Criminal Justice Sciences]] since 2011.<ref name=dallas/> In 2018, he was inducted as a fellow into the UT System Academy of Distinguished Teachers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.utdallas.edu/news/2018/3/29-32905_Criminologist-Named-to-UT-System-Academy-of-Distin_story-wide.html?WT.mc_id=NewsHomePageCenterColumn |title=Criminologist Named to UT System Academy of Distinguished Teachers |date=2018-03-29 |website=University of Texas at Dallas |access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref>
==Editorial activities== Piquero serves on the editorial boards of more than a dozen criminology journals. For five years (2008-2013), he was the co-editor of the ''[[Journal of Quantitative Criminology]]''.<ref name=dallas/> ==Personal life== Piquero's parents migrated to the United States from [[Cuba]] as exiles in the early 1960s. He is married to his colleague, [[Nicole Leeper Piquero]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.utdallas.edu/news/2012/10/30-20461_Ceremonies-Pay-Tribute-to-University-Faculty-and-B_article-wide.html | title=Ceremonies Pay Tribute to University Faculty and Benefactors | publisher=University of Texas at Dallas | work=News Center | date=30 October 2012 | accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.utdallas.edu/news/2011/10/21-13521_University-Celebrates-Achievements-of-Recently-Pub_article-wide.html | title=University Celebrates Achievements of Recently Published Profs | publisher=University of Texas at Dallas | work=News Center | date=21 October 2011 | accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>
