{{Discrimination sidebar}}
'''Gerontophobia''' is the [[Fear processing in the brain|fear]] of growing old, or a hatred or fear of the elderly. The term comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] γέρων – ''gerōn'', "old man"<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dge%2Frwn γέρων], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> and φόβος – ''phobos'', "fear".<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dfo%2Fbos φόβος], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref>
==Ageism== Discriminatory aspects of [[ageism]] have been strongly linked to gerontophobia.<ref>Bunzel, J. H. "Note on the history of a concept-gerontophobia." Gerontologist 12:116-203.</ref> This irrational fear or hatred of the elderly is associated with the fact that someday all young people will grow old and that old age is associated with death. This unwillingness to accept death manifests in feelings of hostility and discriminatory acts towards the elderly.<ref>Levin, J., & Levin, W. C. (1980). Ageism, prejudice and discrimination against the elderly (p. 94). Belmont, Calif.: Wadsworth Pub. Co..</ref>
==See also== * [[Gerascophobia]] * [[Gerontocracy]] * [[List of phobias]]
