'''Igala''' is a [[Volta–Niger languages|Volta–Niger]] language. It is spoken by the [[Igala people|Igala]] [[ethnic group]] of [[Nigeria]]. In 1989 an estimated 800,000 spoke Igala, primarily in [[Kogi State]], but also in fringe portions of [[Delta State]] (Ebu), [[Edo State]] and Anambra state. Dialects include Ebu, Idah, Imane, Ankpa, Dekina, [[Ogugu]], Ibaji and Ife.

The Igala is related to [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]] with which it shares a previous common ancestor, it remains unclear when both language split, mutual intelligibility in modern times is only marginal, although the sound/tonal systems remain the same, akin to the relationship between the various daughter languages of the Romance or Slavic language families. 

The Agatu, [[Idoma people|Idoma]] and [[Basa languages|Bassa]] people use Igala for primary school. The Igala language, as well as Igala culture and tradition, has influenced other languages and cultures around the confluence of the Niger and Benue rivers.

