{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Sri Lankan Gypsy people |image = [[File:Snake charmer(js).jpg|270px]] |image_caption = Sri Lankan Gypsy Snake Charmer |population = |regions = {{flagcountry|Sri Lanka}} |region1 = [[Batticaloa District]] |region2 = |pop1 = |ref1 = |languages = [[Sri Lankan Gypsy Telugu]] , [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] |religions = [[Animism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Hindu]], [[Christianity]] |related = [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]], [[Sri Lankan Tamils]] |footnotes = }} '''Sri Lankan Gypsy people''' are an ethnic group from [[Sri Lanka]] who trace their origins in India (Telugu areas of present Telugu land) centuries ago. They are the only nomadic group of people living in Ceylon and are known as the Ahikuntakas otherwise called Kuravans. They live in small palmyra huts for two or three days in one place. They mostly speak [[Telugu language|Telugu]], also known as [[Sri Lankan Gypsy Telugu]], a [[Dravidian language]] natively spoken in [[India]]. Various governments, [[NGO]]s and [[missionary]] societies have made attempts to settle them down, and thus some are settled in villages. Amongst the majority [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]] speakers they are known as ''ahikuntaka'', while amongst the minority [[Sri Lankan Tamils]] and [[Sri Lankan Moors|Muslims]] they are known as ''[[Kuravar]]''. Some make their living by [[fortune telling]], [[snake charming]] and using monkeys and dogs in performances. Those who are settled in resettlement villages are [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence farmers]] and farm hands to other farmers. They also speak Sinhalese or [[Tamil language|Tamil]] based on their area of settlement. Most seem to be settled in the eastern [[Batticaloa district]]. Most follow rudimentary elements of [[Hinduism]], while some are [[Christians]] and yet others adhere to [[Buddhism]].<ref name="Dilmah">{{cite web|url=http://www.dilmahconservation.org/initiatives/uplifting-the-ahikuntaka-gypsy-community/ |title=Uplifting the ahikuntaka gypsy community |publisher=Dilmah Conservation |accessdate=12 July 2011 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007134011/http://www.dilmahconservation.org/initiatives/uplifting-the-ahikuntaka-gypsy-community/ |archivedate=7 October 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Sunday Times">{{cite news|url=http://sundaytimes.lk/110213/News/nws_13.html|title=By the light of the gypsy fire|date=13 February 2011|accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref><ref name="Wasantha">{{cite web|url=http://www.slageconr.net/slsnet/10thicsls/abstracts/abs165.pdf|title=Gypsy Culture and Society in the Changing World: A Sociological Analysis|last=Subasinghe|first=Wasantha|publisher=University of Kelaniya|accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=McGilvray|first= Dennis|title=Crucible of Conflict: Tamil and Muslim Society on the East Coast of Sri Lanka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MgHIiEtdVFAC&pg=PA49&dq=sri+lanka+%2B+kuravar&hl=en&ei=GNIcTuCYFsa0qgHowZTcCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=kuravar&f=false|year=2008 |publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-4161-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wijesekera |first=Nandadeva |date=1965 |title=The people of Ceylon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DbO1AAAAIAAJ&q=ahikuntakas&dq=ahikuntakas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjnmoy18NDOAhWBNSYKHR5uBDUQ6AEIKjAC |location= |publisher=M.D. Gunasena |page=53 |isbn=}}</ref>
